<tr><td bgcolor="#3F403F" width="98%" class="cheader"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></td><td bgcolor="3F403F" valign="top" align="right" width="22"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/topcorner.gif" width="23" height="22" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" align="right"></td></tr>
<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> V-14 spotlight: Comlink<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=19727'>cedric "simone89" simon</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=19727&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 5, 2008</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Hello to everyone in SWCCG land!!!  I have noticed lately on Decktech there has been a lack of articles regarding actual SWCCG play.  Since today marks one of the biggest games of the SWCCG season the 2008 MPC I have been in a SWCCG mood.  I have decided that I wanted to type up a few words on the newest virtual set.  When I fist saw V14 one of the cards that jumped off the page at me was comlink (v).  I know some of you may be saying that this card is not a top tier card, but I feel it will make it into enough decks this season that it warranted a second look.  The top decks for the dark side in recent events have included Huntdown, LSC, and SYFA.  With SYCFA being knocked down a little bit and the light side looking to tech for Dark side mains, this card could find its way into dark side decks this season to surprise the opposition.  <br />
<br />
Lets start out by looking at the card itself:<br />
Deploy on an Imperial. While present at a battleground (or deployed on Emperor), Imperials lost from Life Force satisfy an additional 2 Force loss. If Luke deploys using your objective, he deploys to Vader&#39;s site (if possible). Once per game, may / Rise, My Friend.<br />
<br />
The card itself starts out as destiny three but if you play biker scout gear you can have a destiny five device floating though the reserve deck.  The card is only pullable with emergency deployment (v) which is not a card I would depend on to pull it  This is one of the things that I feel will keep this card from making it to the top tables this year.  The part I like best about this game text is the fact that one imperial from your life force will count for two force lost.  Meaning if you have twenty imperial characters in your deck it is almost like having an additional 40 life force to lose!!!!!  And yes I know at least one of those has to be on the table with the comlink :P  In a game where the cards are your life force this can give the Dark side an edge over your opponent.  If your opponent drains you for three at Kessel or backdoor/naboo site with a saber, one of your imperials from your life force will satisfy that drain!!!  Turning essentially a loss of three life force into a loss of one life force.  The second part of the card gives a little edge to Bring Him Before Me, but if you want to build a deck around the first line of text I do not think BHBM is the way to go.  <br />
<br />
So what do you think would be the deck to build around this card?  <br />
<br />
RalOps is one deck type that this card will fit into.  I mentioned this briefly on the PCs site and Brad and one of the TX players have also mentioned this, but I will still break it down for those players out there that have not seen those threads.  The biggest advantage with Ralops is from the begining of the game when you get the extra three force for every site you throw down. After that your generation flatlines as Ralops players know.  Another disadvantage I see with RalOps is that all the sites are battlegrounds.  You may ask how that is a bad thing?  Well mostly all the sites are 1/1 sites, so you are giving your opponent all the same icons you are giving yourself.  Occupying battlegrounds is a good thing if you are playing cards like Imperial Decree (v), but you want to be careful not to give your opponent too many force icons.  So basically you activate X force and your opponent activates whatever there deck gives them plus your X. Now once you flip your opponents drains are minus one. Now if the deck is being built around comlink (v) who cares if your opponents drains are minus one. If the opponent initiates a drain of three and you top deck an imperial it covers the force loss whether or not the drain was minus one! The second part of ralops is the extra attrition against your opponent. Due to the low destiny that your imperials have the extra attrition from the seven side of the objective gives you a nice boost when you draw destiny.  Now if you are playing scrub imperials you normally are not going to go around trying to beat up on your opponents jedi.  One of the cards I feel gives ralops an edge is Ralltir Imperial Supply route.  It allows you to put the comlinks back into your used pile when your Imperial leaves the table.  But again it is a 1/1 site just like the rest.      <br />
<br />
Bring him Before me is a deck that I think would have a harder time utilizing the first part of the cards text.  For the most part imperials (save palpy) have destiny too low to make them work in mass in this deck type.   I know that one of the TX players played BHBM with this card, but until I see how that worked I am leery to say that the card would fit into that deck.   <br />
<br />
 Endor Ops is my favorite choice for using this card.  The card that tips the scales over RalOps for me is Establish Secret Base (v).  Wherever you have a trooper your opponent generates no force.  That is the best line in my opinion.  It allows your to generate force and not give any icons up to your opponent.  Put an biker scout trooper at the back door and you basically have a 2/0 site.  Also the card allows you to pull any effect with Endor in the title.  Combat Response, Conduct Your Search, Endor Shield (V), Perimeter Patrol, and S&D are all pullable with this effect.  And endor shield (v) is pullable with the bunker was well!!!  And that is just to name a few cards.  With endor shield (v) out and ESB (v) you will be giving up zero force icons as long as your biker scout or AT-ST controls the site.  The seven side of your objective stops your opponent from cancelling or modifying your drains where you have a biker scout or AT-ST.  Plus on your seven side you get to retrieve one of those biker scout troopers you love so much.  Finally I think that EO is a better call for the meta. WYS I feel will be a big deck seeing as HB and senate took hits with this (v) set (and with the blaster rules change). Also with the new (v) falcon running around you will see life debt and punch it! The 7 side of EO will slow down the extra BD&#39;s.  I will be interested to see the results from the MPC and see how many people played WYS and how many decks used the new falcon.<br />
<br />
Now you may ask What happens when Mace comes down with his saber and overflows your scrub imperials???  The nice thing about EO (over Ralops) is that it gives your opponent very little force.  Mace costs eight by himself, so your opponent will have to put his game on hold to save up long enough to drop mace down on your sites.   Worst case senerio is Mace comes down and battles a lone imperial, hits with his saber and smoke screens.  If you have one power the difference is 12.  If you top deck all imperials you only have to lose four force to cover the overflow; thanks to comlink (v).  And it could be possible that you would not get four imperials in a row but if you are building a deck around this card you would have more imperials then other cards.  Now granted your would not really want to have one lone character and no tricks, but again that is the worst case scenario to make a point.     <br />
<br />
Cards that fit well into decks using this card:  <br />
<br />
Here is a list of a few cards I feel would go well into a deck that is focusing around Comlink (v)<br />
<br />
Imperial Decree (v):  The part of this card I have always liked the best: Whenever you lose Force (except from Force drains, battle damage, or your card), may reduce loss (to a minimum of 1) by the number of battlegrounds you occupy. (Immune to Alter.)   If you are occupying a lot of battle grounds with your scrub imperials (either Ralops or EO), you can slow down the damage from WHAP and Podracing just to name a few.   <br />
<br />
Imperial Domination (v): Deploy on table. If your non-Imperial character or (independent icon) starship on table, this Effect lost. Unless you occupy fewer locations than opponent: if you initiate or win a battle, retrieve an Imperial; during battle, may take an Imperial just drawn for destiny into hand to redraw. (Immune to Alter.)  Win battles retrieve more imperials.  Also if you draw destiny you can take one of those precious imperials into your hand if you wish to cause a re-draw.  <br />
<br />
First Strike:  Always an awesome card to play.  The game text where your opponent must pay to play an interrupt goes along with the force choke theme which I feel is most useful.  Also you can retrieve more imperials among other things. <br />
<br />
Lieutenant Renz (V):  Once per game, if at a battleground site, may initiate a Force drain that cannot be canceled; Force drain is +X (this bonus may not be canceled; ignore other modifiers) where X = the number of unique (*) Stormtroopers at battleground sites.   Drain big once per game while all your troopers are choking your opponent.  <br />
<br />
Forced Servitude (v): Deploy on table. Your troopers are Heroic. Opponent&#39;s total weapon destiny targeting your Heroic cards is +2. When opponent is about to remove their last card from Life Force, you may first place all your troopers in used Pile (last card must still be removed). (Immune to Alter.)  Once you win the game you get to cycle all your lovely troopers back into your life force.  <br />
Outflank (v):  If opponent just initiated battle at a site where their total power is greater than yours, you may use 1 Force (or cause opponent to use 1 Force) to relocate one of your characters or vehicles to that site from a related location.  Very underrated card.  Once your opponent comes after you, play this to bring help from another Endor site.  Also using one of your opponents force helps with the choke.  <br />
<br />
Cease Fire: Protect your troopers.<br />
<br />
Perimeter Patrol:  Slows down your opponent and keeps the big beat down further away.  Pullable with ESB (v) <br />
<br />
Ghhk:  Any deck built around scrub imperials is inherently risky so pack accordingly.<br />
<br />
Trooper Assault:  Immunity to attrition for your scrub imperial troopers.      <br />
<br />
Janus:  Cycle your Imperials back into your life force.  <br />
<br />
Drop non-v:  Would also allow you to cycle during your opponents turn and then lose the cycled imperials to a drain.      <br />
<br />
Well like I said I wanted to write up a few words on my favorite V-14 card Comlink (v).  I dont think you will see it at the top tables this year, but overall I think it is a decent card that will make it into some decks on the local level during this season.  I hope I was able to cover the card well in this article and have introduced some view points for some of our newer players.  To everyone playing in todays MPC good luck and stay safe traveling.<br />
<br />
Thanks for taking the time to read this.<br />
<br />
